column52: Lina works hard to learn the content from two curricula and works well with her co-teachers to plan and deliver effective lessons.
column56: Lina has established sound routines and works well with students in small groups as well as individually. Her class management is most effective and conginial.
column60: These are more advanced skills and Lina has progressed in the use of essential questioning and formative assessment.
column62: We have has several discussions on professional reflection and growth in the areas of student engagement and assessment.

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_10_5) AppleWebKit/602.4.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/10.0
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_10_5) AppleWebKit/602.4.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/10.0.3 Safari/602.4.8
column52: Cody plans well for the diverse student population. He is clear and explanatory in his presentations and has a firm grasp on the subject content.
column56: His lessons move smoothly with routines well established. The culture for learning could be more rigorous but we are working on that aspect of hie professional development.
column60: His questioning skills are still a work in progress as we are trying to get students to think creatively and more independently. Formative assessment techniques are also still in progress.
column62: Cody is open to discussing his performance and improving his effectiveness. He works with his mentor and immediate supervisor in the areas of methodology and assessment.

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_10_5) AppleWebKit/602.4.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/10.0
column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_10_5) AppleWebKit/602.4.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/10.0.3 Safari/602.4.8
column52: Josh is a quick study and has learned a great deal from his co-teachers. He plans collaboratively with both his co-teachers.
column56: I have seen him three times in a self contained class and the culture for learning is quite impressive for a first year teacher. Routines are established and followed for the most part. Severe management issues are handles on an individual basis.
column60: His attempts at using questioning techniques to stimulate thought and discussion are heroic. Most of his students are poorly focused or non verbal but his charm and non threatening demeanor have proven successful in keeping students involved.
column62: Josh is quite frank and self reflective when we meet. He is a good listener and a willing pupil. His growth has been most rewarding.

column52: Zu Bin has a good grasp of the math content but does not sufficiently posses the pedagogy to modify the instruction to meet the needs of his diverse classes.
column56: These are the areas in need of most improvement. His lack of experience with middle school students and unassuming personality have led to his inability to get the class to perform up to their potential.
column60: He plans with essential questions in mind but doesn't quite get the desired results. His activities are engaging but his confusion with the strategy that is being imposed upon him sabotages his lessons. He does have an assessment plan but not for formative evaluation during the lesson.
column62: We have had numerous discussions on his effectiveness and long range plans. He is still in need of professional development in class management and content delivery.

column52: Ms. Armand displayed a solid knowledge of the important concepts in the7th grade math curriculum by creating an imaginative, fun, and engaging math games that reflect important concepts and relationships in the discipline.   The learning objective stated that students will be able to solve one and two step equations by playing several math games. The objective represents important learning within the discipline, and offers students hands on and concrete learning opportunities to develop their understanding of mathematical concepts.  The learning activity will consist of three different games (tic-tac-toe, task cards and "I Can" games.) Students in small groups will rotate through the games. All students must solve the problems individually. Students will take turns attempting problems. If students disagree on an answer, they can discuss it until one student proves to be correct. A learning task such as this encourages responsibility and the ability to work as a team, while simultaneously building their math skills. Ms. Armand will circulate the classroom, facilitate the process, and intervene when conflicting answers are put forth.
column56: The classroom culture exhibited students who are highly motivated and excited about the process of learning. Ms. Armand exhibited trust and confidence in her students by affording them the opportunity to participate in the ultimate student centered activity. Students assume responsibility for their behavior, as well their teammates, and offer assistance to their peers when possible.  Although the noise level was quite high, at times, the healthy hum of excited and engaged students was acceptable. The degree of preplanning, as well as management of the groups, was impressive.   As mentioned, students were loud at times, however, they were redirected rather easily. Virtually no behavioral issues occurred during the lesson.
column60: This lesson centered on hands-on learning games. All questions were built into the three game processes. Based upon the game format, very rich student-to-student discussions were evident. Student thinking and understanding was a main aspect of the games approach. Adequate time was granted for students to problem solve and respond.   Students were intensely engaged during the game process. The content was challenging; however, the team concept provided students with assistance if needed.  Evidence of student learning and understanding was tangible, as students problem solved in their classwork notebooks, which Ms. Armand collects. Final answers were also placed on worksheets provided for the games. Students were also able to supply feedback to their teammates during problem solving.
column62: Ms. Armand was praised for her courage in affording her students the opportunity to participate in a hands-on game format lesson. The degree of preparation put into developing and making the teacher made game cards and materials was significant.  Students were truly enthusiastic, excited and engaged throughout the learning experience. In order for every student to have full access to each of the three games, the lesson duration will be across two days.   At the post observation conference, Ms. Armand and I discussed the importance of debriefing the learning experience with the class, and offering specific feedback as to each students' performance. At times, young students can easily get lost in playing a game, and not realize the value or importance of putting their skills and knowledge to work in different contexts.   This lesson is indicative of a new teacher who is developing the confidence to begin to take risks and experiment. The risk/reward for this lesson was significant as students were fully engaged in the learning process and still having fun.

column52: Ms. Caramanica displayed a solid knowledge the 6th grade ELA curriculum by including the Common Core Learning Standards in her lesson plan. She also included a differentiation/accommodation plan for each of her students.   The instructional objective stated that students will be able to compare and contrast the lives of Jorge and Carlos with the lives of William and Wilbur using a Venn diagram. (The four individuals were the basis of a New York Times Magazine article about two sets of twins who were separated at birth.) The objective represents important learning within the discipline and offers Ms. Caramanica viable methods to assess student understanding.  The learning activity will have students choosing either a comparison/contrast Venn diagram of one set of twins or a history of one of the twins. This assignment represents a significant cognitive challenge for students. Ms. Caramanica offered accommodation plans for each student that could support their efforts in meeting the expectations of the assignment.
column56: Ms. Caramanica has worked hard to build a positive classroom culture centering on learning and working hard. This observation yielded positive advancements in this area, where students conveyed a more consistent level of hard work than in previous observations. Classroom interactions were improved, however, room for growth is evident.  Some instructional time was lost due to disorganized classroom routines and procedures. Students were not assigned a Do Now or entry activity. This led to a loss of approximately 10 minutes at the beginning of the lesson due to students settling down. Additionally, the learning objective was not introduced. Students were just told to begin reading aloud from where they left off in the previous lesson.  An improvement in managing student behavior was noted, however, it is evident that Ms. Caramanica is reticent to redirect or respond to off-task behaviors and talking.
column60: Recall questions pertaining to student understandings related to the article, largely dominated the lesson. Very few students answered questions and, on numerous occasions, answers were called out and were accepted. Student-to-student interactions were non-existent, and virtually no critical thinking questions were offered.  Students' cognitive engagement was inconsistent. Only 3 out of 8 students were on-task for most of the period. The other 5 students exhibited varied levels of engagement and off-task behaviors. Pacing was adequate, however, negative behaviors and off-task talking were tolerated, which disrupted the coherency of the lesson.  It was very difficult to determine students' level of understanding. Very few students answered questions, and no class discussions occurred. Students handed in their comparison/contrast Venn diagram or character study for grading. No other assessment criteria, however, was offered.
column62: Ms. Caramanica and I met for a post observation conference. Despite areas that still require significant attention, this lesson was an improvement over previous lessons. Student behavior was improved, however, Ms. Caramanica must become more diligent in monitoring and redirecting off-task and off-topic verbalizations that interfere with the coherency of her lessons. We discussed, again, that the start of the lesson was very poor, as 10 minutes of instructional time was lost due to poor planning and a lack of a Do Now routine, which has been noted and discussed, in all previous observations. Ms. Caramanica readily recognized the poor start.   Another area that requires immediate attention is to add more inclusive and balanced questioning utilizing the redirection process. Improvement in this area will increase student participation and yield more cognitive engagement.  The overall classroom culture has improved, but hard work and a commitment to learning by students are still very inconsistent. Ms. Caramanica must be more demanding and express higher expectations to her students. Additionally, the use of positive praise and effective feedback, when utilized consistently, will help to build student esteem, as well as offer students an honest assessment of their learning efforts.   Ms. Caramanica's lesson plan was detailed and developed, however, her lesson delivery requires a lot of work. I suggested that she script out her lessons in a very sequential manner, starting with a Do Now and ending with a lesson summary. Diligence and dedication to detail, as well as structure, are of paramount importance to successful lessons and teaching.

column52: Mr. Parson displayed a solid understanding of the 6th grade ELA curriculum by including the Common Core Learning Standards in his lesson plan. He also included a section in his plan that anticipated areas of confusion and possible misunderstandings, so he could address these concerns if they arose.  The instructional objective stated that students will be able to interpret figurative language by finding it, seeing it, feeling it emotionally. This objective represents essential and important learning within the discipline. Differentiation and learning style preferences will help students internalize content material.  The learning activity will require students to choose examples of figurative language with varied degrees of difficulty, and interpret their overall meaning by utilizing four strategies (find it, see it, feel it, get it.) This activity represents a moderate cognitive challenge; however, with supports, students should be able to apply these strategies appropriately.
column56: The culture for learning in Mr. Parson's classroom is very strong. Clearly, students are willing to accept their role in the learning process, as they consistently expend a steady level of effort to succeed. Mr. Parson has high expectations for his students, and is very willing to offer whatever instructional and emotional supports they require to achieve success in his class.  Effective classroom routines and procedures supported the overall success of the lesson. Minimal guidance and prompting was necessary for students to follow expected actions and behaviors.   Student behavior was largely appropriate. When off-task behaviors occurred, Mr. Parson was able to channel and redirect those students to more appropriate behaviors without any loss of instructional time.
column60: Mr. Parson utilized multi-leveled questions to promote student thinking and understanding. He facilitated short student discussions amongst students, where students utilized accountable talk effectively. Wait time was superbly timed, allowing students to digest his questions and formulate their responses.  Mr. Parson incorporated scaffolding to support student understanding. All students were cognitively engaged throughout the lesson. Mr. Parson's presentation style is very dramatic and demonstrative. His students respond with great attentiveness to this approach, as they visibly exhibit a highly positive attitude, enthusiasm, and a joy for learning.  Assessment of student understanding was fully integrated into the lesson through Mr. Parson's use of formative assessments. Students answered questions both verbally and in written form. They utilized accountable talk and participated in lively, short discussions. Students self-assessed, at times, and monitored their own progress.
column62: Mr. Parson offered a very student centered lesson to his students. His students possess a very positive learning vibe and they diligently expend an effort to learn. Mr. Parson's structured and organized teaching approach has allowed this group of self contained, special needs students to improve their academic performance, as well as their behavior. Mr. Parson has had a very positive impact on his students.  Mr. Parson and I discussed strategies that could assist a couple of his students who very rarely speak in class. We talked about setting up predetermined questions that he could share with those students in advance. Those questions can be posed during the lesson at a time designated by Mr. Parson for them to answer. This strategy can build students' self-esteem and confidence, and hopefully lead to regular participation.

column52: Ms. Hogue displayed a solid understanding of the Algebra II curriculum by including the Common Core Learning Standards in her lesson plan.  The learning objective states that students will able to convert degrees to radians, and radians to degrees utilizing two distinct formulas. This objective represents rigorous and important learning within the discipline. It also offers Ms. Hogue viable assessment measures of student understanding.  The learning activity involves students working independently and in small groups solving problems that required them to change radians to degrees and vice versa, using two formulas. Students will be allotted reasonable time to solve the problems. This activity represents a significant cognitive challenge.
column56: The culture for learning in Ms. Hogue's classroom has improved tremendously. It is evident that she and her students value learning and working hard. Students readily accepted their responsibilities, and expended the effort necessary to be successful.  Classroom routines and procedures were effective and supported the overall success of the lesson. Management and monitoring of instructional groups were effective, and offered Ms. Hogue the ability to assist students and assess their understanding.   Student behavior was generally appropriate. When off-task conversations occurred, Ms. Hogue's response was immediate and effective in redirecting negative behaviors.
column60: Most of Ms. Hogue's questions, which did encourage some student thinking and understanding, mostly dealt with the use of the conversion formulas for radians and degrees. Discussions between students occurred predominantly during group work; however, very few students participated or volunteered responses during Ms. Hogue's questioning episodes.  The learning task challenged student thinking. A number of students asked clarifying questions during group work, and virtually all students were engaged throughout the lesson.  Ms. Hogue diligently monitored student understanding during the independent practice stage of the lesson. She offered feedback to some students, and answered clarifying questions for a few students as well. Student worksheets were collected for grading.
column62: At the post observation conference, Ms. Hogue was praised for her structured and well-delivered lesson. She was much more organized, confident and prepared for this lesson as compared to previous lessons. Ms. Hogue mentioned that colleagues in the math department have been offering her very valuable and much desired support. They have helped her to take advantage of materials of instruction, teaching strategies and resources readily available from the textbook publisher. They have also been instrumental in offering her guidance and emotional support in general.  Ms. Hogue's diligent monitoring of her students during group work, as well as her consistent attention in redirecting off-task students, were areas that have shown noticeable improvement. Ms. Hogue's questioning still tends to be single line of inquiry, and we discussed ways that further efforts can be devoted to the redirection process and encouraging more student-to-student dialogue.

column13: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_12_4) AppleWebKit/603.1.30 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/10.1 Safari/603.1.30
column52: Ms. Vieira demonstrated a solid knowledge of the 6th grade ELA curriculum by including the Common Core Learning Standards in her lesson plan. She also included the period's agenda, which supported the emotional needs of the more anxious students in her class.  The lesson objective stated that students would determine the meaning of figurative language to assist them in understanding the text. This objective represents important learning within the ELA curriculum and offered Ms. Vieira ample assessment opportunities.  The learning activity had students investigating selected examples from the K.K. Rowling novel, Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone. They had to identify an example of the figurative language utilized, wither metaphor, simile, idiom or onomatopoeia, and then record what the example means. This activity represents a significant cognitive challenge. Appropriate use of instructional groups will afford students the ability to dialogue with each other to generate the best answer.
column56: Ms. Vieira and her co-teacher have established a very healthy culture for learning in their classroom. It is evident that the students and teachers value learning and working hard. Students understand their role and, for the most part, expend an effort to learn.   Classroom routines and procedures are effective and support the teaching and learning process. Management of instructional groups and transitions contribute to the overall flow and coherency of the lesson.  Student behavior was entirely appropriate. Students took an active role in monitoring their own behavior in a very mature manner. Students were respectful of their peers and their teachers.
column60: Both teachers took an active role in posing questions to students. The questions promoted student thinking and understanding of figurative language. Redirection, appropriate pacing and student-to-student dialogue afforded many, if not all students, a voice during the lesson.  Students were engaged intellectually throughout the lesson. Both teachers made positive use of high student interest in the text to offer very challenging examples of figurative language and fully expand student thinking.   Posed questions and monitoring of student progress and level of understanding during group work served as formative assessments during the lesson. Completed classwork was collected and would later serve as a more summative check of student understanding. Effective feedback and praise was not offered to students during the lesson.
column62: Ms. Vieira and I met for a post observation conference. Both teachers took an active role in presenting the lesson and assessing students throughout the period. The relationship between the two teachers and the overall coherency of the co-planned lesson resulted in a very interesting and successful lesson. All students were cognitively engaged and behaved in a very mature manner. The lesson was challenging but, due to the popularity of the Harry Potter text, all students were highly motivated. The pace of the lesson was comfortable and met the needs of all the students.  Ms. Vieira was praised for all the areas stated above. I inquired as to why effective feedback and praise was not employed during the lesson. She stated that this particular class has been great from the start, and that they are extremely self-motivated. We discussed the value of effective feedback and praise for students. Although feedback and praise was not utilized in this particular lesson, I feel confident that Ms. Vieira will incorporate both into her lessons from this point.

column52: Ms. Martin displayed a solid understanding of the Algebra II curriculum by including the Common Core Learning Standards in her lesson plan. She also included a section of her plan indicating supplemental work for students who complete their work early.   The learning objective stated that students will be able to construct a table and scatter plot of the population of Senegal. This objective represents rigorous and important learning within the discipline. It also offered an imaginative and interesting strategy for teaching scatter plot diagrams and graphs.  The lesson activity asks students to utilize Google Classroom and construct a table describing population data for Senegal from 1955-present. They will then create a scatter plot graph based on the data they collected. This activity represents a significant cognitive challenge, however, ample time allocations, as well as direct teacher support, will assist students in meeting the lesson objective.
column56: Ms. Martin's classroom exhibits a culture where students and teacher value learning and working hard. Students appear to understand their role in the learning process, and consistently expend an effort to learn.   Effective classroom routines and procedures supported students' learning efforts. Minimal guidance and prompting was required for students to comply with classroom expectations.   Most student behavior was appropriate, however, Ms. Martin had issues with four students who required a significant degree of redirection. She explained that the graph they were being asked to construct is part of their math portfolio, and it must be handed in by March 20th as a graduation requirement. Ms. Martin was diligent in monitoring their behaviors; however, she was unsuccessful in getting them to do any work.
column60: Ms. Martin utilized directed and clarifying questions to drive the guided practice portion of the lesson, where she modeled the process of creating a scatter plot diagram. Since this largely was a hands-on lesson, very few group discussions took place.   Most students were cognitively engaged throughout the lesson, except the four students mentioned above who were off-task. The appropriate pacing of the lesson provided students with ample time to complete their work. Ms. Martin monitored student work carefully and was ever present to offer support to students when needed.  Assessment was regularly utilized throughout the lesson. For most of the lesson, students worked independently to gather data and construct their graphs. During this time, Ms. Martin circulated from student to student, monitoring student work, and assessing their level of understanding and their progress. She directly questioned them, at times, offering specific feedback to advance their learning.
column62: The learning environment for this lesson was calm, supportive and productive. Ms. Martin explained the task well, and modeled the process of constructing the scatter point graph effectively. She offered ample support and time for students to complete the task, which is a graduation requirement. Even when four students were off-task, and virtually doing no work, she patiently explained what their task was, and why they had to do it. Her level of patience was extraordinary. Ms. Martin possesses a calm and caring affect in which most students respond well to.   Ms. Martin offered effective feedback to students, however, no positive praise was offered at all. At the post observation conference, Ms. Martin related that the lesson was going so well, that she had no excuse for not praising the nine students who were doing quality work. I reminded her of the Penny Project where the pennies serve as tangible reminders to praise students for their efforts during the lesson. She said she would try to improve in this area.

column52: Ms. Zheng displayed a solid understanding of the Algebra II curriculum by including the Common Core Learning Standards in her lesson plan.   The learning objective stated that students will be able to explain how the probability of an event is dependent on the sample space and conclude that it lies between zero and one inclusive. This objective represents rigorous and important learning within the discipline, and affords Ms. Zheng ample opportunities to assess student understanding.  The learning activity will consist of students supplying missing Venn diagram elements, including referenced elements of the sets, in a Probability and Set Theory Worksheet. This activity represents a significant cognitive challenge, which requires reasonable time allocations and assistance from peers.
column56: Ms. Zheng's classroom culture exhibits an environment where students and teacher value learning. Virtually all students understand their role as learners, and consistently expend an effort to learn.   Classroom routines and procedures supported the overall effectiveness of the lesson. Minimal guidance and prompting was required for students to follow classroom routines.   Student behavior was entirely appropriate. Students were mature, responsible, and responsive to the needs of their group members.
column60: Ms. Zheng posed multi-leveled questions that promoted student thinking and understanding. Her questions were largely single inquiry; however, genuine discussions between students occurred during group work.   Virtually all students were intellectually engaged throughout the well-designed learning tasks. The pacing of the lesson provided students ample time to engage in the content.   Ms. Zheng diligently monitored student progress during group work. She utilized directed questions, prompts, and student feedback to diagnose evidence of learning. Student worksheets were collected for grading.
column62: Ms. Zheng was praised for her well-planned and delivered lesson. Her students were engaged, worked diligently, and their behavior was excellent. Ms. Zheng incorporated more student centered approaches and activities, and reduced her level of lecturing. Students were engaged in the act of doing, which created more critical thinking opportunities for all.   Ms. Zheng's lesson delivery approach has improved tremendously. She still needs to incorporate the redirection process to increase student participation, as well as further incorporation of effective and purposeful feedback into her teaching.

column52: Mr. Di Donato displayed a solid understanding of the 6th grade math curriculum by including the Common Core Learning Standards in his lesson plan.   The lesson objective stated that students will be able to generate equivalent numerical expressions using prime factors. The objective represents rigorous and important learning within the discipline. It also affords Mr. Di Donato ample assessment opportunities.  The learning activity will consist of students working independently on a worksheet that asks them to find the prime factors of six numbers. The learning experience represents a significant cognitive challenge for Mr. Di Donato's group of special needs students.
column56: Mr. Di Donato's classroom is a vibrant learning environment where students and teacher share the values of working hard, learning, and having fun. Students understand their role as learners, and consistently expend an effort to learn.   Classroom routines and procedures support instruction, which contributed to the success of the lesson. Students required minimal guidance and prompting to follow classroom routines and procedures.   Student behavior was entirely appropriate. Students monitored their own behavior, and respected the needs of their classmates.
column60: Mr. Di Donato posed questions at varied levels, designed to promote student thinking and understanding. At times, students dialogued with each other, and utilized accountable talk during discussions. He provided ample wait time, and attempted to create opportunities for all of his students to participate in discussions.   All of Mr. Di Donato's students were intellectually engaged during the lesson. He utilized scaffolding, and incorporated assistive modifications to assist students in increasing their engagement. Many student responses and connections were well beyond expected levels for self-contained students.   Mr. Di Donato built assessment opportunities into instruction. Students verbally and in written form, responded to posed questions. He and his paraprofessionals offered feedback that was accurate and specific, which advanced student learning. He monitored all students carefully during the lesson for evidence of learning. Classwork was collected for grading.
column62: At the post observation conference, Mr. Di Donato was praised for his well planned and delivered lesson. His students are severely academically challenged, at the supportive learning environment he has created has assisted them in learning at levels that are well beyond expectations. It is very evident that Mr. Di Donato has built a very special and healthy rapport with his students. They appear confident, willing to participate and are responsive to his efforts, as well as their classmates'. Mr. Di Donato makes learning fun for them, with his dramatic and engaging presentation style. The four paraprofessionals work as a team to assist all students, not just the individual students they are assigned to work with.  Mr. Di Donato has high expectations. At the post observation conference, we discussed increasing the level of rigor in class, to push students beyond their comfort level. He explained that they surprise him everyday. Just when he believes that he tapped into their frustration level, they move past it. We discussed progress monitoring in reading, writing and math to truly gauge the levels of student understanding.  Mr. Di Donato is a very positive, hard working and dedicated teacher. He appears to love teaching, and is a natural educator. The positive effect he has had on his students helps them significantly in their academic and emotional efforts. His goal is to have all of his students achieve at a level that he can recommend them for, at least, a partial ICT program.

column52: Mr. Palsgrove displayed a moderate understanding of the geometry curriculum by including the common core learning standards in his lesson. His lesson plan was very cursory, and did not contain support strategies or teacher actions that would enhance student understanding.  The learning objective stated, "How does a dilation transform a figure?" Although this learning objective represents rigorous and important learning, it does not correlate with Charlotte Danielson's model as to exactly what students will be able to understand, know and do by the end of the learning period.   The learning activities center on students completing dilation problems individually and in pairs. The activities represent a significant cognitive challenge, and ample time will be afforded to students to reflect, think, and formulate responses.
column56: Mr. Palsgrove is still in the process of building a classroom culture that centers on learning and working hard. A number of his students do not work diligently from bell to bell, and engage in off-task conversations. Most of the other students do their work, however, they are extremely chatty. At present, Mr. Palsgrove is not exemplifying a teacher who has high expectations for his students.   Classroom routines and procedures were organized and purposeful. Instructional materials were prepared in advance, and handed out by Mr. Palsgrove himself.  Mr. Palsgrove's behavior management approach requires more consistency of effort. He does not intervene to disengage off-task student conversations on a consistent basis. At times, he appears to be hesitant to confront students who are interfering in the teaching a learning process.
column60: Mr. Palsgrove posed questions that promoted student thinking and understanding. His questions were single line of inquiry with no redirection strategies. Mr. Palsgrove experienced difficulty engaging his students in discussions, since off-task talking interrupted the flow of the lesson on an ongoing basis throughout the period.  Most students were engaged intellectually during the independent and group practice stages of the lesson. The pace of the lesson was appropriate for the needs of his students; however, active engagement was interrupted by Mr. Palsgrove's intermittent need to manage off-task students.   Mr. Palsgrove actively monitored his students' level of understanding while circulating the classroom. He spent productive time with virtually every pair or small group. He offered specific feedback to a few students, but largely he questioned or prompted to diagnose evidence of learning. Worksheets were collected for grading. No summary or reflection took place at the end of the lesson.
column62: Mr. Palsgrove possesses effective technical pedagogical skills. His lesson was well planned and delivered. He offered ample guided and independent practice. His questioning afforded students adequate wait time. Mr. Palsgrove was responsive to student needs and monitored student understanding consistently.   The overwhelming weakness in Mr. Palsgrove's teaching is in behavior management. His students were largely engaged cognitively; however, incessant chatter broke the continuity and flow of the lesson. Some students talked all period long. Mr. Palsgrove made attempts to disengage the talking; however, it was feeble. His responses to misbehavior were slow, and lacked a definitive message that this behavior will not be tolerated. We discussed this issue at the post observation conference. Initially, he attempted to downplay the situation; however, he quickly recognized that his ineffectual behavior management approach had a negative effect on his lesson. We discussed revisiting the standards of conduct by eliciting student opinions and recommendations. The hope is that what students help to create, they will support. We also discussed consistently praising students who are engaged in positive actions virtually all period. Finally, Mr. Palsgrove must develop a "teacher voice" when responding to misbehavior. His timid approach is clearly not working. He must be quick to respond with a stern and purposeful voice and manner that sends the message that inappropriate behaviors will not be tolerated.
